406:/*
407:    The third critical signal for DRAM access is the MUX signal which switches the address lines on the DRAM
408:    from the ROW to the COLUMN address.  This much be done after the RAS signal has gone to 0, and before the 
409:    CAS signal goes to 0.  There is RAS holdtime requirement of 10ns, and CAS setup requirement if 10ns, and a 
410:    MUX propegation delay of at least 7ns.
411:
412:    The solution is the change the MUX signal based on the DRAM_ACCESS_RAS signal.  As soon as the RAS signal goes low, 
413:    the MUX signal will start to change.  The MUX change will be 7.5ns behind the RAS signal, and the MUX itself
414:    will take another 7ns to change outputs.  This will give the needed RAS hold time.
415:
416:    MUX = 0 for ROW address, 1 for COL address.  Reset puts it at 0. 
417:*/
